			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65346067" name="comment_link_65346067" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23680929&amp;cid=65346067" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65346067)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65346067" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65346067); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~mysidia">mysidia</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~mysidia">( 191772 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65346067"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65346067"><p>Huge difference for this case.  The PIN is only locally significant and used to unlock a credential stored on your device.<br>Your PIN is never sent over the network like a login password is.</p><p>What makes passwords vulnerable is they are used directly in an authentication protocol.<br>With locally-sigificant PINs the PIN is not part of the authentication protocol.   The authenticator is on your computer,<br>and the PIN is simply used as an additional factor to unlock the authenticator on your computer.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65346067">

